LL(1) Parser Documentation
Overview
This program implements an LL(1) parser for a unit conversion domain-specific language (DSL). It performs lexical and syntactic analysis, producing a parse tree in father-sibling representation.
Components
1. Scanner (Lexer)

Input: Source code string
Output: PIF (Program Internal Form) - sequence of tokens
Method: Uses regular expressions representing Finite Automata for:

Identifiers: [a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*
Constants: 0|[1-9][0-9]*


Classifies keywords, units, operators, and delimiters

2. Grammar

LL(1) grammar for the DSL (left-recursion eliminated)
Computes FIRST sets: terminals that can start each non-terminal
Computes FOLLOW sets: terminals that can follow each non-terminal
Builds parsing table M[non-terminal, terminal] using FIRST/FOLLOW

3. LL(1) Parser

Algorithm: Top-down predictive parsing
Data structures:

Stack: holds grammar symbols
Input buffer: holds tokens from PIF
Parsing table: guides production selection


Process:

Start with start symbol on stack
If stack top matches input → consume both
If stack top is non-terminal → lookup production in table, expand
If epsilon production → pop stack without consuming input
Continue until stack empty and input consumed



4. Parse Tree Output

Father-sibling representation: Each node stores:

id: unique identifier
symbol: grammar symbol
father: parent node ID
sibling: right sibling ID


Output format: Table with Index, Symbol, Value, Father, Sibling columns